Project Blueprint: COSC878 Journal Article

1. Project Identity

Course: COSC878 - Web and Social Media Analytics

Assignment: Research Article Development

Official Title: "An Aspect-Based Multi-Agent Framework for Consumer Behavior Analytics: A Case Study of the Mobile Phone Accessories Market on Jumia Nigeria"

2. The Core Problem

E-commerce platforms in Nigeria (like Jumia) generate massive amounts of consumer feedback. However, standard analytics fall short because:

Star Ratings are Deceptive: A 4-star review might contain critical text about a product breaking after two weeks.

Basic Sentiment Analysis Fails: Traditional tools classify an entire review as simply "Positive" or "Negative." They cannot handle mixed reviews (e.g., "Great battery, but delivery took a month").

Localized Noise: Nigerian reviews contain unique slang, grammatical variations, and specific geographical delivery complaints that standard lexicons struggle to process.

3. The Innovative Solution (Multi-Agent Framework)

Instead of a single, basic sentiment model, this project proposes a Multi-Agent AI Pipeline. Think of it as a team of specialized AI workers analyzing each review:

Agent 1 (The Cleaner/Router): Takes the scraped raw text, cleans it, and identifies the product type (e.g., Power Bank vs. Earbuds).

Agent 2 (The Aspect Extractor): Reads the review and isolates the specific features being discussed (e.g., Battery Life, Build Quality, Delivery Speed, Price).

Agent 3 (The Contextual Classifier): Assigns a specific sentiment score (Positive/Negative/Neutral) to each isolated aspect, accounting for local context.

4. Data Strategy

Target Source: Jumia Nigeria (Verified Customer Feedback sections).

Target Category: Mobile Phone Accessories (specifically high-volume items like Portable Power Banks, Chargers, and Gaming Finger Sleeves).

Why this works: Mobile accessories have highly consistent consumer expectations (it either charges fast/lasts long or it doesn't), making the AI's job highly accurate and focused.

5. Technology Stack & Rubric Alignment

This project is designed to maximize the 55% grading criteria by utilizing multiple required tools:

Data Collection (Web Scraping): Using BeautifulSoup in Python to scrape Jumia review titles, text bodies, star ratings, and dates.

Data Analysis (Machine Learning/AI): Using Python to orchestrate the multi-agent LLM workflow alongside tools like NLTK/VADER for baseline sentiment processing.

Data Presentation (Visualization/Dashboarding): Using Matplotlib or Streamlit to build interactive charts comparing sentiment across different aspects (e.g., showing that Ace Elec power banks have great battery sentiment but poor delivery sentiment).

